---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { internalHref, siteMeta } from "@/lib/site";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Runtime And Libraries Reference"
  description="Current runtime and library reference for Kern: the base/sys/rt/std split, startup ownership, and libc policy."
>
  <section class="doc-shell">
    <div class="section-lead max-w-4xl">
      <div class="eyebrow">Runtime And Libraries</div>
      <h1 class="mt-6 max-w-4xl text-5xl leading-[0.95] text-[color:var(--kern-ink)] md:text-6xl">
        Runtime and libraries
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
        This page describes the current `base` / `sys` / `rt` / `std` split, startup ownership,
        libc policy, and the explicit toolchain axes that decide how a program is brought up.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-shell section-divider">
    <div class="section-lead">
      <div class="eyebrow">Layers</div>
      <h2 class="mt-4 text-4xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">Library layers</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="doc-topic-grid mt-8">
      <section>
        <div class="doc-topic-title">`base`</div>
        <ul class="doc-topic-list">
          <li>Runtime-independent foundation types, memory primitives, and containers.</li>
          <li>The narrowest official layer for freestanding-oriented work.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
      <section>
        <div class="doc-topic-title">`sys` and `rt`</div>
        <ul class="doc-topic-list">
          <li>`sys` covers operating-system and provider boundaries.</li>
          <li>`rt` provides startup glue and minimal runtime support.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
      <section>
        <div class="doc-topic-title">`std`</div>
        <ul class="doc-topic-list">
          <li>User-facing Kern code built on `base` plus `sys`.</li>
          <li>Hosted is an environment question, not a claim that libc defines the language.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-shell section-divider">
    <div class="section-lead">
      <div class="eyebrow">Axes</div>
      <h2 class="mt-4 text-4xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">The runtime choices the toolchain makes explicit</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="dense-link-list mt-8">
      <div class="dense-link-item">
        <div class="dense-link-title">`runtime_entry`</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">Chooses startup ownership: `none`, `rt`, or `crt`.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="dense-link-item">
        <div class="dense-link-title">`runtime_libc`</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">Chooses whether libc is linked. Kern itself stays freestanding in the language sense.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="dense-link-item">
        <div class="dense-link-title">`library_bundle`</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">Chooses which official root aliases are wired: `none`, `base`, or `std`.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="dense-link-item">
        <div class="dense-link-title">Provider choice</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">`sys` and `rt` implementation choice stays in normal module and package wiring rather than a dedicated provider flag.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-shell section-divider">
    <div class="section-lead">
      <div class="eyebrow">Policy</div>
      <h2 class="mt-4 text-4xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">Current model</h2>
    </div>
    <ul class="doc-bullet-columns mt-8">
      <li>The language itself is freestanding.</li>
      <li>`std` remains valid without libc.</li>
      <li>Hosted is an OS and process-environment concern rather than a C-language concern.</li>
      <li>Libc is an optional compatibility boundary rather than the semantic base of Kern programs.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-shell section-divider">
    <div class="section-lead">
      <div class="eyebrow">Guide</div>
      <h2 class="mt-4 text-4xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">Related guide chapters</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="dense-link-list mt-8">
      <a class="dense-link-item" href={internalHref("/guide/libraries-and-runtime/")}>
        <div class="dense-link-title">Libraries and runtime</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">How the official library layers fit together and where startup ownership lives.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="dense-link-item" href={internalHref("/guide/c-interop-and-libc/")}>
        <div class="dense-link-title">C interop and libc</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">When libc matters, when it does not, and how that boundary stays explicit.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="dense-link-item" href={internalHref("/guide/standard-library-tour/")}>
        <div class="dense-link-title">Standard library tour</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">A user-facing path through the current `std` surface.</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-shell section-divider">
    <div class="section-lead">
      <div class="eyebrow">Authority</div>
      <h2 class="mt-4 text-4xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">Current authoritative source</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="dense-link-list mt-8">
      <a class="dense-link-item" href={`${siteMeta.repoUrl}/blob/main/docs/runtime-architecture.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
        <div class="dense-link-title">Open `docs/runtime-architecture.md`</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">The runtime architecture document for the `base` / `sys` / `rt` / `std` split and the surrounding policy.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="dense-link-item" href={internalHref("/reference")}>
        <div class="dense-link-title">Back to the reference index</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">Language, compiler, package, and runtime tracks in one place.</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
